    <title>Cells in Cartilage Activity</title>
    <page>
        <question id="_u5_levels_cells_inline1">
            <body>Chondrocytes perform similar functions to which bone cells?</body>
            <multiple_choice shuffle="false" id="ans">
                <choice value="a">osteoblasts</choice>
                <choice value="b">osteoclasts</choice>
                <choice value="c">osteocytes</choice>
                <choice value="d">none of the above</choice>
            </multiple_choice>
            <part>
                <response match="b" score="0">
                    <feedback>Incorrect.</feedback>
                </response>
                <response match="c" score="0">
                    <feedback>Incorrect.</feedback>
                </response>
                <response match="c" score="1">
                    <feedback>That's right! Cytes means cells. Chondrocytes are the primary cell
                        type in cartilage just like osteocytes are the primary cell type in bone.
                    </feedback>
                </response>
                <response match="d" score="0">
                    <feedback>Incorrect.</feedback>
                </response>
                <hint>look at the roots of the word</hint>
                <hint>they sense damage and send signals to repair it</hint>
            </part>
        </question>
        <question id="_u5_levels_cells_inline2">
            <body>Which cell type is found in bone that is not found in cartilage?</body>
            <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
                <choice value="a">osteoblasts</choice>
                <choice value="b">osteoclasts</choice>
                <choice value="c">osteocytes</choice>
                <choice value="d">none of the above</choice>
            </multiple_choice>
            <part>
                <response match="a" score="0">
                    <feedback>Incorrect. From the root of the word, osteoblasts are like
                        chondroblasts.</feedback>
                </response>
                <response match="c" score="0">
                    <feedback>Incorrect. Osteocytes are like chondrocytes.</feedback>
                </response>
                <response match="b" score="1">
                    <feedback>That's right. Cartilage doesn't have cells to break extracellular
                        matrix down. Bone is much more stiff and dense. Cartilage is usually broken
                        down by proteolysis and injury.</feedback>
                </response>
                <response match="d" score="0">
                    <feedback>Incorrect. There are three bone cells and two cartilage cells. Their
                        action is not one for one.</feedback>
                </response>
                <hint>Think about how the native collagen is formed.</hint>
            </part>
        </question>
